# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vendoring-dependencies
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] In software engineering, **coupling** is the degree of interdependence between software modules, a measure of how closely connected two routines or modules are, and the strength of the relationships between modules.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling is not binary but multi-dimensional.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling is usually contrasted with cohesion.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Low coupling often correlates with high cohesion, and vice versa.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Low coupling is often thought to be a sign of a well-structured computer system and a good design, and when combined with high cohesion, supports the general goals of high readability and maintainability.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] The software quality metrics of coupling and cohesion were invented by Larry Constantine in the late 1960s as part of a structured design, based on characteristics of “good” programming practices that reduced maintenance and modification costs.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Structured design, including cohesion and coupling, were published in the article *Stevens, Myers & Constantine* (1974) and the book *Yourdon & Constantine* (1979), and the latter subsequently became standard terms.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling and cohesion are terms which occur together very frequently.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling refers to the interdependencies between modules, while cohesion describes how related the functions within a single module are.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Low cohesion implies that a given module performs tasks which are not very related to each other and hence can create problems as the module becomes large.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling can be "low" (also "loose" and "weak") or "high" (also "tight" and "strong").
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] A module here refers to a subroutine of any kind, i.e. a set of one or more statements having a name and preferably its own set of variable names.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Content coupling is said to occur when one module uses the code of another module, for instance a branch.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Common coupling is said to occur when several modules have access to the same global data.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] But it can lead to uncontrolled error propagation and unforeseen side-effects when changes are made.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] This is basically related to the communication to external tools and devices.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Control coupling is one module controlling the flow of another, by passing it information on what to do (e.g., passing a what-to-do flag).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] and use only parts of it, possibly different parts (e.g., passing a whole record to a function that needs only one field of it).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] In this situation, a modification in a field that a module does not need may lead to changing the way the module reads the record.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] , even if they do not utilize the modified attribute.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Data coupling occurs when modules share data through, for example, parameters.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Each datum is an elementary piece, and these are the only data shared (e.g., passing an integer to a function that computes a square root).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Describes the relationship between a child and its parent.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] The child is connected to its parent, but the parent is not connected to the child.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] It is when two actions are bundled together into one module just because they happen to occur at the same time.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] In recent work various other coupling concepts have been investigated and used as indicators for different modularization principles used in practice.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] The goal of defining and measuring this type of coupling is to provide a run-time evaluation of a software system.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] It has been argued that static coupling metrics lose precision when dealing with an intensive use of dynamic binding or inheritance.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] In the attempt to solve this issue, dynamic coupling measures have been taken into account.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] This kind of a coupling metric considers the conceptual similarities between software entities using, for example, comments and identifiers and relying on techniques such as latent semantic indexing (LSI).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Assembly of modules might require more effort and/or time due to the increased inter-module dependency.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] A particular module might be harder to reuse and/or test because dependent modules must be included.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Longer messages require more CPU and memory to produce.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] To optimize runtime performance, message length must be minimized and message meaning must be maximized.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Since a message must be transmitted in full to retain its complete meaning, message transmission must be optimized.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Longer messages require more CPU and memory to transmit and receive.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Also, when necessary, receivers must reassemble a message into its original state to completely receive it.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Hence, to optimize runtime performance, message length must be minimized and message meaning must be maximized.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Message protocols and messages themselves often contain extra information (i.e., packet, structure, definition and language information).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Hence, the receiver often needs to translate a message into a more refined form by removing extra characters and structure information and/or by converting values from one type to another.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Any sort of translation increases CPU and/or memory overhead.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] To optimize runtime performance, message form and content must be reduced and refined to maximize its meaning and reduce translation.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] All messages must be interpreted by the receiver.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Simple messages such as integers might not require additional processing to be interpreted.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] messages require a parser and a string transformer for them to exhibit intended meanings.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] To optimize runtime performance, messages must be refined and reduced to minimize interpretation overhead.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] One approach to decreasing coupling is functional design, which seeks to limit the responsibilities of modules along functionality.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Low coupling refers to a relationship in which one module interacts with another module through a simple and stable interface and does not need to be concerned with the other module's internal implementation (see Information Hiding).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Systems such as CORBA or COM allow objects to communicate with each other without having to know anything about the other object's implementation.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Both of these systems even allow for objects to communicate with objects written in other languages.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling describes the degree and nature of dependency between software components, focusing on what they share (e.g., data, control flow, technology) and how tightly they are bound.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] It evaluates two key dimensions: strength, which measures how difficult it is to change the dependency, and scope (or visibility), which indicates how widely the dependency is exposed across modules or boundaries.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Traditional coupling types typically include content coupling, common coupling, control coupling, stamp coupling, external coupling, and data coupling.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Connascence, introduced by Meilir Page-Jones, provides a systematic framework for analyzing and measuring coupling dependencies.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Connascence can be categorized into static (detectable at compile-time) and dynamic (detectable at runtime) forms.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Static connascence refers to compile-time dependencies, such as method signatures, while dynamic connascence refers to runtime dependencies, which can manifest in forms like connascence of timing, values, or algorithm.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Each coupling flavor can exhibit multiple types of connascence, a specific type, or, in rare cases, none at all, depending on how the dependency is implemented.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Common types of connascence include connascence of name, type, position, and meaning.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Certain coupling types naturally align with specific connascence types; for example, data coupling often involves connascence of name or type.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] However, not every combination of coupling and connascence is practically meaningful.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Dependencies relying on parameter order in a method signature demonstrate connascence of position, which is fragile and difficult to refactor because reordering parameters breaks the interface.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] In contrast, connascence of name, which relies on field or parameter names, is generally more resilient to change.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Connascence types themselves exhibit a natural hierarchy of strength, with connascence of name typically considered weaker than connascence of meaning.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Dependencies spanning module boundaries or distributed systems typically have higher coordination costs, increasing the difficulty of refactoring and propagating changes across distant boundaries.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Modern practices, such as dependency injection and interface-based programming, are often employed to reduce coupling strength and improve the maintainability of dependencies.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] While coupling identifies what is shared between components, connascence evaluates how those dependencies behave, how changes propagate, and how difficult they are to refactor.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Strength, locality, and degree are interrelated; dependencies with high strength, wide scope, and spanning distant boundaries are significantly harder to refactor and maintain.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Together, coupling provides a high-level overview of dependency relationships, while connascence offers a granular framework for analyzing dependency strength, locality, degree, and resilience to change, supporting the design of maintainable and robust systems.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling in Software Engineering describes a version of metrics associated with this concept.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/coupling-computer-programming] `Coupling(C)` makes the value larger the more coupled the module is.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] In software development, a **fork** is a codebase that is created by duplicating an existing codebase and, generally, is subsequently modified independently of the original.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] Software built from a fork initially has identical behavior as software built from the original code, but as the source code is increasingly modified, the resulting software tends to have increasingly different behavior compared to the original.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] A fork is a form of branching, but generally involves storing the forked files separately from the original – not in the repository.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] Reasons for forking a codebase include user preference, stagnated or discontinued development of the original software or a schism in the developer community.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] Forking proprietary software (such as Unix) is prohibited by copyright law without explicit permission, but free and open-source software, by definition, may be forked without permission.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] The word *fork* has been used to mean "to divide in branches, go separate ways" as early as the 14th century.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] The term was in use on Usenet by 1983 for the process of creating a subgroup to move topics of discussion to.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] Although *fork* is not known to have been used in the sense of a community schism during the origins of Lucid Emacs (now XEmacs) (1991) or the Berkeley Software Distributions (BSDs) (1993–1994), Russ Nelson used the term *shattering* in this sense in 1993 (attributing it to John Gilmore).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] In 1995, *fork* was used to describe the XEmacs split, and was an understood usage in the GNU Project by 1996.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] The word is used similarly for the fork() system call which causes a running process to split in two – typically, to allow them to perform different tasks in parallel.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] In free software, forks often result from a schism over different goals or personality clashes.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] In a fork, both parties assume nearly identical code bases, but typically only the larger group, or whoever controls the web site, will retain the full original name and the associated user community.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] Thus, there is a reputation penalty associated with forking.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] The relationship between the different teams can be cordial or very bitter.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] On the other hand, a *friendly fork* or a *soft fork* is a fork that does not intend to compete, but wants to eventually merge with the original.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] Raymond, in his essay *Homesteading the Noosphere*, stated that "The most important characteristic of a fork is that it spawns competing projects that cannot later exchange code, splitting the potential developer community".
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] Distributed revision control (DVCS) tools have popularised a less emotive use of the term "fork", blurring the distinction with "branch".
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] With a DVCS such as Mercurial or Git, the normal way to contribute to a project, is to first create a personal branch of the repository, independent of the main repository, and later seek to have your changes integrated with it.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] Forks often restart version numbering from numbers typically used for initial versions of programs like 0.0.1, 0.1, or 1.0 even if the original software was at another version such as 3.0, 4.0, or 5.0.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] An exception is sometimes made when the forked software is designed to be a drop-in replacement for the original project, *e.g.* MariaDB for MySQL or LibreOffice for OpenOffice.org.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] The BSD licenses permit forks to become proprietary software, and copyleft proponents say that commercial incentives thus make proprietisation almost inevitable.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] Some of these vendors contribute back changes to the community project, while some keep their changes as their own competitive advantages.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] In proprietary software, the copyright is usually held by the employing entity, not by the individual software developers.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] Proprietary code is thus more commonly forked when the owner needs to develop two or more versions, such as a windowed version and a command line version, or versions for differing operating systems, such as a word processor for IBM PC compatible machines and Macintosh computers.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] Generally, such internal forks will concentrate on having the same look, feel, data format, and behavior between platforms so that a user familiar with one can also be productive or share documents generated on the other.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] This is almost always an economic decision to generate a greater market share and thus pay back the associated extra development costs created by the fork.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/fork-software-development] A notable proprietary fork not of this kind is the many varieties of proprietary Unix—almost all derived from AT&T Unix under license and all called "Unix", but increasingly mutually incompatible.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] In version-control systems, a **monorepo** or **monorepository** ("mono" meaning 'single' and "repo" being short for 'repository') is a software-development strategy in which the code for a number of projects is stored in the same repository.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] This practice dates back to at least the early 2000s, when it was commonly called a shared codebase.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] Google, Meta, Microsoft, Uber, Airbnb, and Twitter all employ very large monorepos with varying strategies to scale build systems and version control software with a large volume of code and daily changes.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] A related concept is a monolithic application, but whereas a monolith combines its sub-projects into one large project, a monorepo may contain multiple independent projects.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] In a multiple repository environment where multiple projects depend on a third-party dependency, that dependency might be downloaded or built multiple times.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] In a monorepo the build can be easily optimized, as referenced dependencies all exist in the same codebase.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] When projects that work together are contained in separate repositories, releases need to sync which versions of one project work with the other.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] In a monorepo this problem can be negated, since developers may change multiple projects atomically.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] Since developers have access to the entire project, refactors can ensure that every piece of the project continues to function after a refactor.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] teams can improve projects being worked on by other teams.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] Although not required, some monorepo builds use one version number across all projects in the repository.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] With split repositories, access to a repository can be granted based upon need.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] A monorepo allows read access to all software in the project, possibly presenting new security issues.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] Note that there are versioning systems in which this limitation is not an issue.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] is used, it's possible to download any part of the repo (even a single directory), and path-based authorization can be used to restrict access to certain parts of a repository.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] With split repositories, you fetch only the project you are interested in by default.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] This can take up a significant amount of storage space.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] doing so defeats some of the advantages of a monorepo.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] Companies with large projects have come across hurdles with monorepos, specifically concerning build tools and version control systems.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] Google's monorepo, speculated to be the largest in the world, meets the classification of an ultra-large-scale system and must handle tens of thousands of contributions every day in a repository over 80 terabytes in size.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] Companies using or switching to existing version control software found that software could not efficiently handle the amount of data required for a large monorepo.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] Facebook and Microsoft chose to contribute to or fork existing version control software Mercurial and Git respectively, while Google eventually created their own version control system.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] For more than ten years, Google had relied on Perforce hosted on a single machine.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] In 2005 Google's build servers could get locked up to 10 minutes at a time.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] Google improved this to 30 seconds–1 minute in 2010.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] Due to scaling issues, Google eventually developed its own in-house distributed version control system dubbed Piper.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] Facebook ran into performance issues with the version control system Mercurial and made upstream contributions to the client, and in January 2014 made it faster than a competing solution in Git.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] In May 2017 Microsoft announced that virtually all of its Windows engineers use a Git monorepo.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] In the transition, Microsoft made substantial upstream contributions to the Git client to remove unnecessary file access and improve handling of large files with Virtual File System for Git.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] Few build tools work well in a monorepo, and flows where builds and continuous integration testing of the entire repository are performed upon check-in will cause performance problems.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] A build system that processes dependencies as a directed graph (such as Buck, Bazel, Please, or Pants) solves this by compartmentalizing each build or test to the active area of development.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] Twitter began development of Pants in 2011, as both Facebook's Buck and Google's Bazel were closed-source at the time.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] Twitter open-sourced Pants in 2012 under the Apache 2.0 License.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/monorepo] Please is a Go-based build system; it was developed in 2016 by Thought Machine, whose developers were both inspired by Google's Bazel and dissatisfied with Facebook's Buck.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] A **package manager**, or **package management system**, is software that supports installing, upgrading, configuring, and removing software for the host system in a consistent manner.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] A package manager deals with *packages*, distributions of software and data in archive files.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Packages contain metadata, such as the software's name, description of its purpose, version number, vendor, checksum (usually a cryptographic hash function), and a list of dependencies necessary for the software to run properly.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Upon installation, metadata is stored in a local package database.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Package managers typically maintain a database of software dependencies and version information to prevent software mismatches and missing prerequisites.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] They work closely with software repositories, binary repository managers, and app stores.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Package managers are designed to eliminate the need for manual installs and updates.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] This can be particularly useful for large enterprises whose operating systems (OSes) typically consist of hundreds or even tens of thousands of distinct packages.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] An early package manager was SMIT (and its backend install) from IBM AIX.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] SMIT was introduced with AIX 3.0 in 1989.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Package managers like dpkg have existed as early as 1994.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Early package managers, from around 1994, had no automatic dependency resolution but could already simplify the process of adding and removing software from a running system.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] By around 1995, beginning with CPAN, package managers began handling package repository downloads, and dependency resolution and installation as needed, making it easier to install, uninstall and update software.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] A software package is an archive file containing a computer program as well as necessary metadata for its deployment.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] The program may be in source code that has to be compiled and built first.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Package metadata include the software's description, version number, and dependencies.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Package managers are charged with the task of finding, installing, maintaining or uninstalling packages upon the user's command.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Computer systems that rely on dynamic library linking, instead of static library linking, share executable libraries of machine instructions across packages and applications.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] In these systems, conflicting relationships between different packages requiring different versions of libraries results in a situation called *dependency hell*.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] On Microsoft Windows systems, this is also called *DLL hell* when working with dynamically-linked libraries.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Modern package managers have mostly solved these problems by allowing parallel installation of multiple library versions (e.g.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] OPENSTEP's *Framework* system), a dependency of any kind (e.g.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] *slots* in Gentoo Portage), and even packages compiled with different compiler versions (e.g. dynamic libraries built by the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, where a stable ABI does not exist), in order to enable other packages to specify which version they are linked or installed against.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] System administrators may install and maintain software using tools other than package managers.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] For example, a local administrator may download unpackaged source code, compile it, and install it.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] This may cause the local system to fall out of synchronization with the package manager's database.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] The local administrator will be required to take additional measures, such as manually managing some dependencies or integrating the changes into the package manager.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] There are tools to ensure that locally-compiled packages are integrated with the package management.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Upgrades of configuration files may be particularly troublesome.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Since package managers, at least on Unix systems, originated as extensions of file archivers, they can usually only overwrite or retain configuration files, rather than apply rules to them.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] There are exceptions to this that usually apply to kernel configuration (which, if broken, will render the computer unusable after a restart).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Problems can be caused if the configuration file format changes; for instance, if the old file does not explicitly disable new options that should be disabled.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Some package managers, such as Debian's dpkg, allow configuration during installation.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] In other situations, packages are installed with the default configuration, which is then overwritten, for example in headless installations to a large number of computers.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] This kind of pre-configured installation is also supported by dpkg.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] To give users more control over the software they allow to be installed on their systems, and sometimes due to legal or convenience reasons on the distributors' side, packages are often downloaded from software repositories.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Many package managers can be configured to never upgrade certain packages, or to upgrade them only when critical vulnerabilities or instabilities are found in the previous version, as defined by the packager of the software.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] This process is called *upgrade suppression*, or *version pinning*.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Some of the more advanced package management features offer *cascading package removal*, in which all packages that depend on the target package and all packages that only it depends on are also removed.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Although commands are specific to each package manager, they are translatable to a large extent, as most package managers offer similar functions.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] The Arch Linux wiki offers an extensive overview of commands.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Linux distributions oriented to binary packages rely heavily on package management systems as their primary means of managing and maintaining software.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Mobile operating systems such as Android (Linux-based) and iOS (Unix-based) rely almost exclusively on their respective vendors' app stores and thus use their own dedicated package management systems.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] A package manager is often called an *install manager*, which can lead to a confusion between package managers and installers.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Most software configuration management systems treat building software and deploying software as separate, independent steps.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] A build automation utility typically takes human-readable source code files already on a computer, and automates the process of converting them into an executable package on the same or a remote computer.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Later, a package manager typically running on another computer downloads the pre-built executable and installs it.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] A few tools, such as Maak and A-A-P, are designed to handle both building and deployment, and can be used as either build automation utilities, package managers, or both.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] App stores can also be considered application-level package managers (without the ability to install all levels of programs).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Unlike traditional package managers, app stores are designed to enable payment for the software itself (instead of for software development), and may only offer monolithic packages with no dependencies or dependency resolution.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] They are usually limited in their management functionality, due to focusing on ease-of-use over power or emergence, and are common in commercial operating systems and smart devices.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Package managers also often have only human-reviewed code.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Many app stores, such as Google Play and Apple's App Store, mainly screen apps using automated tools only; malware can pass these tests by detecting when the app is being tested, and delaying malicious activity.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] There are exceptions: the npm package database, for instance, relies entirely on post-publication review of its code, while the Debian package database has an extensive human review process before any package goes into the main database.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] The XZ Utils backdoor used years of trust-building to insert a backdoor, which was nonetheless caught while in the testing database.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Also known as binary repository manager, it is a software tool designed to optimize the download and storage of binary files, artifacts and packages used and produced in the software development process.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] These package managers aim to standardize the way enterprises treat all package types.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] They give users the ability to apply security and compliance metrics across all artifact types.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Universal package managers have been referred to as being at the center of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Each package manager relies on the format and metadata of the packages in its repository.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] That is, package managers need groups of files to be bundled along with appropriate metadata, such as dependencies.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Often, a core set of utilities manages the basic installation from these packages and multiple package managers use these utilities to provide additional functionality.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] For example, yum relies on rpm as a backend.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Yum extends the functionality of rpm by adding features such as simple configuration for maintaining a network of systems.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] As another example, the Synaptic Package Manager provides a graphical user interface by using the Advanced Packaging Tool (apt) library, which in turn relies on dpkg for core functionality.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Alien is a program that converts between different Linux package formats, supporting conversion between Linux Standard Base (LSB) compliant .rpm packages, .deb, Stampede (.slp), Solaris (.pkg) and Slackware (.tgz, .txz, .tbz, .tlz) packages.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] For mobile operating systems, Google Play uses the Android application package (APK) package format while Microsoft Store uses the APPX and XAP formats.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Both Google Play and Microsoft Store have eponymous package managers.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] By the nature of free and open-source software (FOSS), packages under similar and compatible licenses are available on a number of operating systems.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] These packages can be combined and distributed using configurable packaging systems to handle many permutations of software and manage version-specific dependencies and conflicts.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Some managers of FOSS packages are released as FOSS themselves.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] The ability to continuously upgrade third-party software is typically added by adding the URL of the corresponding repository to the package management's configuration file.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Besides system-level application managers, there are add-on package managers for operating systems with limited capabilities and for programming languages in which developers need the latest libraries.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Unlike system-level package managers, application-level package managers focus on a small part of the software system.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] They typically reside within a directory tree that is not maintained by the system-level manager, such as c:\cygwin or /opt/sw.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] This may not be the case for managers that deal with programming libraries, leading to possible conflicts, as both managers may claim to own a file and may break upgrades.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] Ian Murdock commented that package management is "the single biggest advancement Linux has brought to the industry", that it blurs the boundaries between operating systems and applications, and that it makes it "easier to push new innovations [...] into the marketplace and [...] evolve the OS".
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] There is also a conference for package manager developers known as PackagingCon.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/package-manager] It was established in 2021 with the aim to understand different approaches to package management.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] In computing, **source code**, or simply **code** or **source**, is human readable plain text that can eventually result in controlling the behavior of a computer.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] In order to control a computer, it must be processed by a computer program – either executed directly via an interpreter or translated into a more computer-consumable form such as via a compiler.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Sometimes, code is compiled directly to machine code so that it can be run in the native language of the computer without further processing.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Many modern environments, though, involve compiling to an intermediate representation such as bytecode that can either run via an interpreter or be compiled on-demand to machine code via just-in-time compilation.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] The first programmable computers, which appeared at the end of the 1940s, were programmed in machine language (simple instructions that could be directly executed by the processor).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Machine language was difficult to debug and was not portable between different computer systems.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Initially, hardware resources were scarce and expensive, while human resources were cheaper.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] As programs grew more complex, programmer productivity became a bottleneck.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] This led to the introduction of high-level programming languages such as Fortran in the mid-1950s.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] These languages abstracted away the details of the hardware, and were designed to express algorithms that could be understood more easily by humans.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] As instructions distinct from the underlying computer hardware, software is therefore relatively recent, dating to these early high-level programming languages such as Fortran, Lisp, and Cobol.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] The invention of high-level programming languages was simultaneous with the compilers needed to translate the source code automatically into machine code that can be directly executed on the computer hardware.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Source code is the form of code that is modified directly by humans, typically in a high-level programming language.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Object code can be directly executed by the machine and is generated automatically from the source code, often via an intermediate step, assembly language.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] While object code will only work on a specific platform, source code can be ported to a different machine and recompiled there.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] For the same source code, object code can vary significantly—not only based on the machine for which it is compiled, but also based on performance optimization from the compiler.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Most programs do not contain all the resources needed to run them and rely on external libraries.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Part of the compiler's function is to link these files in such a way that the program can be executed by the hardware.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Software developers often use configuration management to track changes to source code files (version control).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] The configuration management system also keeps track of which object code file corresponds to which version of the source code file.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] The number of source lines of code (SLOC) is often used as a metric when evaluating the productivity of computer programmers, the economic value of a code base, effort estimation for projects in development, and the ongoing cost of software maintenance after release.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Source code is also used to communicate algorithms between parties, e.g., code snippets online or in books.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Computer programmers can find it helpful to review extant source code to learn about programming techniques.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] The sharing of source code between developers is often cited as a contributing factor to the maturing of their programming skills.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Some consider source code an expressive artistic medium.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Source code often contains comments—blocks of text marked for the compiler to ignore.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] This content is not part of the program logic, but is instead intended to help readers understand the program.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Companies often keep the source code confidential in order to hide algorithms considered a trade secret.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Proprietary, secret source code and algorithms are widely used for sensitive government applications such as criminal justice, which results in black box behavior with a lack of transparency into the algorithm's methodology.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] The result is avoidance of public scrutiny of issues such as bias.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Access to the source code (not just the object code) is essential to modifying it.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Understanding extant code is necessary to understand how it works and before modifying it.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] The rate of understanding depends both on the code base as well as the skill of the programmer.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Experienced programmers have an easier time understanding what the code does at a high level.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Software visualization is sometimes used to speed up this process.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Many software programmers use an integrated development environment (IDE) to improve their productivity.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] IDEs typically have several features built in, including a source-code editor that can alert the programmer to common errors.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Modification often includes code refactoring (improving structure without changing function) and restructuring (improving structure and function simultaneously).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Nearly every change to code introduces new bugs or unexpected ripple effects, which require another round of fixes.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Code reviews by other developers are often used to scrutinize new code added to a project.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] The purpose of this phase is often to verify that the code meets style and maintainability standards and that it is a correct implementation of the software design.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] According to some estimates, code review dramatically reduce the number of bugs persisting after software testing is complete.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Along with software testing that works by executing the code, static program analysis uses automated tools to detect problems with the source code.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Many IDEs support code analysis tools, which might provide metrics on the clarity and maintainability of the code.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Debuggers are tools that often enable programmers to step through execution while keeping track of which source code corresponds to each change of state.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Source code files in a high-level programming language must go through a stage of preprocessing into machine code before the instructions can be carried out.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] After being compiled, the program can be saved as an object file and the loader (part of the operating system) can take this saved file and execute it as a process on the computer hardware.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Some programming languages use an interpreter instead of a compiler.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] An interpreter converts the program into machine code at run time, which makes them 10 to 100 times slower than compiled programming languages.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Source code was used this way to distribute the Unix operating system early in the history of Unix, and later to allow programs written in scripting languages (in particular the JavaScript client-side scripting language) to run on a wide variety of machines.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Software quality is an overarching term that can refer to a code's correct and efficient behavior, its reusability and portability, or the ease of modification.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] It is usually more cost-effective to build quality into a product from the start rather than try to add it later in a development process.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Higher quality code reduces lifetime cost to both suppliers and customers as via higher reliability and maintainability.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Maintainability is the quality of software enabling it to be easily modified without breaking extant functions.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Following coding conventions such as using clear function and variable names that correspond to their purpose makes maintenance easier.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Use of conditional loop statements only if the code could execute more than once, and eliminating code that will never execute can also increase understandability.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Many software development organizations neglect maintainability during the development phase, even though it will increase long-term costs.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Technical debt is incurred when programmers, often out of laziness or urgency to meet a deadline, choose quick and dirty solutions rather than build maintainability into their code.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] A common cause is underestimates in software development effort estimation, leading to insufficient resources allocated to development.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] A challenge with maintainability is that many software engineering courses do not emphasize it.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Development engineers who know that they will not be responsible for maintaining the software do not have an incentive to build in maintainability.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] The situation varies worldwide, but in the United States before 1974, software and its source code was not copyrightable and therefore always public domain software.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] In 1974, the US Commission on New Technological Uses of Copyrighted Works (CONTU) decided that "computer programs, to the extent that they embody an author's original creation, are proper subject matter of copyright".
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] Proprietary software is rarely distributed as source code.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/source-code] The free reusability of open-source software can speed up development.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Version control is a component of software configuration management.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] A **version control system** is a software tool that automates version control.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Alternatively, version control is embedded as a feature of some systems such as word processors, spreadsheets, collaborative web docs, and content management systems, such as Wikipedia's page history.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Version control includes options to view old versions and to revert a file to a previous version.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] As teams develop software, it is common to deploy multiple versions of the same software, and for different developers to work on one or more different versions simultaneously.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Bugs or features of the software are often only present in certain versions (because of the fixing of some problems and the introduction of others as the program develops).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Therefore, for the purposes of locating and fixing bugs, it is vitally important to be able to retrieve and run different versions of the software to determine in which version(s) the problem occurs.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] It may also be necessary to develop two versions of the software concurrently: for instance, where one version has bugs fixed, but no new features (branch), while the other version is where new features are worked on (trunk).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] At the simplest level, developers could simply retain multiple copies of the different versions of the program, and label them appropriately.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] This simple approach has been used in many large software projects.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] While this method can work, it is inefficient as many near-identical copies of the program have to be maintained.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] This requires a lot of self-discipline on the part of developers and often leads to mistakes.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Since the code base is the same, it also requires granting read-write-execute permission to a set of developers, and this adds the pressure of someone managing permissions so that the code base is not compromised, which adds more complexity.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Consequently, systems to automate some or all of the revision control process have been developed.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] This abstracts most operational steps (hides them from ordinary users).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Moreover, in software development, legal and business practice, and other environments, it has become increasingly common for a single document or snippet of code to be edited by a team, the members of which may be geographically dispersed and may pursue different and even contrary interests.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Sophisticated revision control that tracks and accounts for ownership of changes to documents and code may be extremely helpful or even indispensable in such situations.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Revision control may also track changes to configuration files, such as those typically stored in `/etc` or `/usr/local/etc` on Unix systems.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] This gives system administrators another way to easily track changes made and a way to roll back to earlier versions should the need arise.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Many version control systems identify the version of a file as a number or letter, called the *version number*, *version*, *revision number*, *revision*, or *revision level*.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] For example, the first version of a file might be version *1*.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] When the file is changed the next version is *2*.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Each version is associated with a timestamp and the person making the change.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Revisions can be compared, restored, and, with some types of files, merged.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] IBM's OS/360 IEBUPDTE software update tool dates back to 1962, arguably a precursor to version control system tools.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Two source management and version control packages that were heavily used by IBM 360/370 installations were The Librarian and Panvalet.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] A full system designed for source code control was started in 1972: the Source Code Control System (SCCS), again for the OS/360.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] SCCS's user manual, especially the introduction, which was published on December 4, 1975, implied that it was the first deliberate revision control system.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The Revision Control System (RCS) followed in 1982 and, later, Concurrent Versions System (CVS) added network and concurrent development features to RCS.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] After CVS, a dominant successor was Subversion, followed by the rise of distributed version control tools such as Git.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Revision control manages changes to a set of data over time.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] These changes can be structured in various ways.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Often the data is thought of as a collection of many individual items, such as files or documents, and changes to individual files are tracked.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] This is in line with the notion of keeping files separate but causes problems when identity changes, which happens when files are renamed, split or merged.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Accordingly, some systems such as Git, consider changes to the data as a whole instead, which is less intuitive for simple changes but simplifies more complex changes.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] As a simple example, when editing a computer file, the data stored in memory by the editing program is the working copy, which is committed by saving the file.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Concretely, one may print out a document, edit it by hand, and only later manually input the changes into a computer and save it.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] For source code control, the working copy is instead a copy of all files in a particular revision, generally stored locally on the developer's computer; in this case saving the file only changes the working copy, and checking into the repository is a separate step.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] If multiple people are working on a single data set or document, they are implicitly creating branches of the data (in their working copies), and thus issues of merging arise, as discussed below.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] For simple collaborative document editing, this can be prevented by using file locking or simply avoiding working on the same document that someone else is working on.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Revision control systems are often centralized, with a single authoritative data store, the *repository,* and check-outs and check-ins done with reference to this central repository.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Alternatively, in distributed revision control, no single repository is authoritative, and data can be checked out and checked into any repository.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] When checking into a different repository, this is interpreted as a merge or patch.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] In terms of graph theory, revisions are generally thought of as a line of development (the *trunk*) with branches off of this, forming a directed tree, visualized as one or more parallel lines of development (the "mainlines" of the branches) branching off a trunk.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] In reality the structure is more complicated, forming a directed acyclic graph, but for many purposes "tree with merges" is an adequate approximation.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Revisions occur in sequence over time, and thus can be arranged in order, either by revision number or timestamp.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Revisions are based on past revisions, though it is possible to largely or completely replace an earlier revision, such as "delete all existing text, insert new text".
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] In the simplest case, with no branching or undoing, each revision is based on its immediate predecessor alone, and they form a simple line, with a single latest version, the "HEAD" revision or *tip*.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] In graph theory terms, drawing each revision as a point and each "derived revision" relationship as an arrow (conventionally pointing from older to newer, in the same direction as time), this is a linear graph.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] In principle the resulting tree need not have a preferred tip ("main" latest revision) – just various different revisions – but in practice one tip is generally identified as HEAD.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] When a new revision is based on HEAD, it is either identified as the new HEAD, or considered a new branch.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] This most often occurs when changes occur in multiple branches (most often two, but more are possible), which are then merged into a single branch incorporating both changes.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] If these changes overlap, it may be difficult or impossible to merge, and require manual intervention or rewriting.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] In the presence of merges, the resulting graph is no longer a tree, as nodes can have multiple parents, but is instead a rooted directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The graph is acyclic since parents are always backwards in time, and rooted because there is an oldest version.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Assuming there is a trunk, merges from branches can be considered as "external" to the tree – the changes in the branch are packaged up as a *patch,* which is applied to HEAD (of the trunk), creating a new revision without any explicit reference to the branch, and preserving the tree structure.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Thus, while the actual relations between versions form a DAG, this can be considered a tree plus merges, and the trunk itself is a line.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] In distributed revision control, in the presence of multiple repositories these may be based on a single original version (a root of the tree), but there need not be an original root - instead there can be a separate root (oldest revision) for each repository.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] This can happen, for example, if two people start working on a project separately.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Similarly, in the presence of multiple data sets (multiple projects) that exchange data or merge, there is no single root, though for simplicity one may think of one project as primary and the other as secondary, merged into the first with or without its own revision history.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Engineering revision control developed from formalized processes based on tracking revisions of early blueprints or bluelines*"MIL-STD-100G: Department of Defense Standard Practice for Engineering Drawings" (PDF).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] This system of control implicitly allowed returning to an earlier state of the design, for cases in which an engineering dead-end was reached in the development of the design.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] A revision table was used to keep track of the changes made.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Additionally, the modified areas of the drawing were highlighted using revision clouds.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Version control is widespread in business and law.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Indeed, "contract redline" and "legal blackline" are some of the earliest forms of revision control, and are still employed in business and law with varying degrees of sophistication.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The most sophisticated techniques are beginning to be used for the electronic tracking of changes to CAD files (see product data management), supplanting the "manual" electronic implementation of traditional revision control.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Game development often involves large binary files and teams working together across different disciplines.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] As a result, game studios use version control systems with good support for large binary files, file locking, and fast synchronization.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Common tools include Perforce and several newer cloud-based systems.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Traditional revision control systems use a centralized model where all the revision control functions take place on a shared server.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] If two developers try to change the same file at the same time, without some method of managing access the developers may end up overwriting each other's work.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Centralized revision control systems solve this problem in one of two different "source management models": file locking and version merging.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] An operation is *atomic* if the system is left in a consistent state even if the operation is interrupted.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The *commit* operation is usually the most critical in this sense.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Commits tell the revision control system to make a group of changes final, and available to all users.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Not all revision control systems have atomic commits; Concurrent Versions System lacks this feature.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The simplest method of preventing "concurrent access" problems involves locking files so that only one developer at a time has write access to the central "repository" copies of those files.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Once one developer "checks out" a file, others can read that file, but no one else may change that file until that developer "checks in" the updated version (or cancels the checkout).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] File locking has both merits and drawbacks.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] It can provide some protection against difficult merge conflicts when a user is making radical changes to many sections of a large file (or group of files).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] If the files are left exclusively locked for too long, other developers may be tempted to bypass the revision control software and change the files locally, forcing a difficult manual merge when the other changes are finally checked in.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] In a large organization, files can be left "checked out" and locked and forgotten about as developers move between projects - these tools may or may not make it easy to see who has a file checked out.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Most version control systems allow multiple developers to edit the same file at the same time.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The first developer to "check in" changes to the central repository always succeeds.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The system may provide facilities to merge further changes into the central repository, and preserve the changes from the first developer when other developers check in.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Merging two files can be a very delicate operation, and usually possible only if the data structure is simple, as in text files.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The result of a merge of two image files might not result in an image file at all.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The second developer checking in files will need to take care with the merge, to make sure that the changes are compatible and that the merge operation does not introduce its own logic errors within the files.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] These problems limit the availability of automatic or semi-automatic merge operations mainly to simple text-based documents, unless a specific merge plugin is available for the file types.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The concept of a *reserved edit* can provide an optional means to explicitly lock a file for exclusive write access, even when a merging capability exists.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Most revision control tools will use only one of these similar terms (baseline, label, tag) to refer to the action of identifying a snapshot ("label the project") or the record of the snapshot ("try it with baseline *X*").
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Typically only one of the terms *baseline*, *label*, or *tag* is used in documentation or discussion ; they can be considered synonyms.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] In most projects, some snapshots are more significant than others, such as those used to indicate published releases, branches, or milestones.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] When both the term *baseline* and either of *label* or *tag* are used together in the same context, *label* and *tag* usually refer to the mechanism within the tool of identifying or making the record of the snapshot, and *baseline* indicates the increased significance of any given label or tag.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Most formal discussion of configuration management uses the term *baseline*.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Distributed revision control systems (DRCS) take a peer-to-peer approach, as opposed to the client–server approach of centralized systems.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Rather than a single, central repository on which clients synchronize, each peer's working copy of the codebase is a bona-fide repository.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Distributed revision control conducts synchronization by exchanging patches (change-sets) from peer to peer.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Rather, communication is only necessary when pushing or pulling changes to or from other peers.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Following best practices is necessary to obtain the full benefits of version control.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Best practice may vary by version control tool and the field to which version control is applied.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Other software development best practices such as code review and automated regression testing may assist in the following of version control best practices.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Costs and benefits will vary dependent upon the version control tool chosen and the field in which it is applied.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] This section speaks to the field of software development, where version control is widely applied.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] In addition to the costs of licensing the version control software, using version control requires time and effort.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The concepts underlying version control must be understood and the technical particulars required to operate the version control software chosen must be learned.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Version control best practices must be learned and integrated into the organization's existing software development practices.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Management effort may be required to maintain the discipline needed to follow best practices in order to obtain useful benefit.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] A core benefit is the ability to keep history and revert changes, allowing the developer to easily undo changes.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] This gives the developer more opportunity to experiment, eliminating the fear of breaking existing code.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Branching assists with deployment and release management.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] There can be damage mitigation, accountability, process and design improvement, and other benefits associated with the record keeping provided by version control, the tracking of who did what, when, why, and how.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] When bugs arise, knowing what was done when helps with damage mitigation and recovery by assisting in the identification of what problems exist, how long they have existed, and determining problem scope and solutions.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Previous versions can be installed and tested to verify conclusions reached by examination of code and commit messages.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Version control can greatly simplify debugging.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The application of a test case to multiple versions can quickly identify the change which introduced a bug.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The developer need not be familiar with the entire code base and can focus instead on the code that introduced the problem.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Version control enhances collaboration in multiple ways.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Since version control can identify conflicting changes, i.e. incompatible changes made to the same lines of code, there is less need for coordination among developers.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The packaging of commits, branches, and all the associated commit messages and version labels, improves communication between developers, both in the moment and over time.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Better communication, whether instant or deferred, can improve the code review process, the testing process, and other critical aspects of the software development process.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Some of the more advanced revision-control tools offer many other facilities, allowing deeper integration with other tools and software-engineering processes.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Plugins are often available for IDEs such as Oracle JDeveloper, IntelliJ IDEA, Eclipse, Visual Studio, Delphi, NetBeans IDE, Xcode, and GNU Emacs (via vc.el).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Advanced research prototypes generate appropriate commit messages.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] An approved revision of a document or source file to which subsequent changes can be made.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] A search for the author and revision that last modified a particular line.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] A set of files under version control may be *branched* or *forked* at a point in time so that, from that time forward, two copies of those files may develop at different speeds or in different ways independently of each other.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] A *change* (or *diff*, or *delta*) represents a specific modification to a document under version control.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The granularity of the modification considered a change varies between version control systems.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] On many version control systems with atomic multi-change commits, a *change list* (or *CL*), *change set*, *update*, or *patch* identifies the set of *changes* made in a single commit.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] This can also represent a sequential view of the source code, allowing the examination of source as of any particular changelist ID.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] To *check out* (or *co*) is to create a local working copy from the repository.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] A user may specify a specific revision or obtain the latest.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The term 'checkout' can also be used as a noun to describe the working copy.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] When a file has been checked out from a shared file server, it cannot be edited by other users.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Think of it like a hotel, when you check out, you no longer have access to its amenities.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] In version control software, a changeset (also known as commit and revision) is a set of alterations packaged together, along with meta-information about the alterations.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] A changeset describes the exact differences between two successive versions in the version control system's repository of changes.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Changesets are typically treated as an atomic unit, an indivisible set, by version control systems.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] To *commit* (*check in*, *ci* or, more rarely, *install*, *submit* or *record*) is to write or merge the changes made in the working copy back to the repository.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] A commit contains metadata, typically the author information and a commit message that describes the change.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] A short note, written by the developer, stored with the commit, which describes the commit.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Ideally, it records why the modification was made, a description of the modification's effect or purpose, and non-obvious aspects of how the change works.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] A conflict occurs when different parties make changes to the same document, and the system is unable to reconcile the changes.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] A user must *resolve* the conflict by combining the changes, or by selecting one change in favour of the other.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Most revision control software uses delta compression, which retains only the differences between successive versions of files.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] This allows for more efficient storage of many different versions of files.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] A stream in which some or all file versions are mirrors of the parent stream's versions.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The process of merging changes made in the main *trunk* into a development (feature or team) branch.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Also sometimes called *tip*, this refers to the most recent commit, either to the trunk or to a branch.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The trunk and each branch have their own head, though HEAD is sometimes loosely used to refer to the trunk.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Some revision control software uses Interleaved deltas, a method that allows storing the history of text based files in a more efficient way than by using Delta compression.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] When a developer *locks* a file, no one else can update that file until it is unlocked.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Locking can be supported by the version control system, or via informal communications between developers (aka *social locking*).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Similar to *trunk*, but there can be a mainline for each branch.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] A *merge* or *integration* is an operation in which two sets of changes are applied to a file or set of files.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The act of copying file content from a less controlled location into a more controlled location.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] For example, from a user's workspace into a repository, or from a stream to its parent.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Copy revisions from one repository into another.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] *Pull* is initiated by the receiving repository, while *push* is initiated by the source.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] *Fetch* is sometimes used as a synonym for *pull*, or to mean a *pull* followed by an *update*.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Contributions to a source code repository that uses a distributed version control system are commonly made by means of a pull request, also known as a merge request.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The contributor requests that the project maintainer *pull* the source code change, hence the name "pull request".
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The maintainer has to *merge* the pull request if the contribution should become part of the source base.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The developer creates a pull request to notify maintainers of a new change; a comment thread is associated with each pull request.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] This allows for focused discussion of code changes.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Submitted pull requests are visible to anyone with repository access.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] A pull request can be accepted or rejected by maintainers.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Once the pull request is reviewed and approved, it is merged into the repository.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Depending on the established workflow, the code may need to be tested before being included into official release.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Therefore, some projects contain a special branch for merging untested pull requests.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Other projects run an automated test suite on every pull request, using a continuous integration tool, and the reviewer checks that any new code has appropriate test coverage.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] In version control systems, a repository is a data structure that stores metadata for a set of files or directory structure.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Depending on whether the version control system in use is distributed, like Git or Mercurial, or centralized, like Subversion, CVS, or Perforce, the whole set of information in the repository may be duplicated on every user's system or may be maintained on a single server.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Some of the metadata that a repository contains includes, among other things, a historical record of changes in the repository, a set of commit objects, and a set of references to commit objects, called *heads*.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The act of user intervention to address a conflict between different changes to the same document.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The process of merging different team branches into the main trunk of the versioning system.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] In SVK, a Revision is the state at a point in time of the entire tree in the repository.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The act of making one file or folder available in multiple branches at the same time.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] When a shared file is changed in one branch, it is changed in other branches.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] A container for branched files that has a known relationship to other such containers.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] Streams form a hierarchy; each stream can inherit various properties (like versions, namespace, workflow rules, subscribers, etc.) from its parent stream.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] A *tag* or *label* refers to an important snapshot in time, consistent across many files.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] These files at that point may all be tagged with a user-friendly, meaningful name or revision number.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] An *update* (or *sync*, but *sync* can also mean a combined *push* and *pull*) merges changes made in the repository (by other people, for example) into the local *working copy*.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] *Update* is also the term used by some CM tools (CM+, PLS, SMS) for the change package concept (see *changelist*).
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] The *working copy* is the local copy of files from a repository, at a specific time or revision.
[src:vendoring-dependencies/version-control] All work done to the files in a repository is initially done on a working copy, hence the name.
